The Cinderteeth -- Prism Archive, Founding Record

When the founders of Kiess broke ground on Evermeet's ruins, they
found an obsidian disc in the collapsed civic hall bearing the
triune seal of the Spirebound Conclave: Ember, Prism, Pale. That
disc proved Evermeet had signed sealed warrants transferring its
own citizens to the Conclave's custody. The Cinderteeth Mountains
are not distant geology to Kiess. They are the origin point of
the abuse that wrote our founding charter.

The Conclave built their sanctum in the Western Fold precisely
because isolation made accountability impossible. They embedded
resonance crystals throughout the Bellspine ridge, instruments
no one could audit. When they collapsed, those anchors were never
retrieved. This is sealed-warrant thinking writ in stone: an
authority that installs infrastructure, extracts compliance, and
then vanishes, leaving the consequences for others to manage.

The Trade Syndics track the Cinderteeth for a more immediate
reason: seismic risk to western routes. The mountains are coupled
to deep continental faults. Tremors propagate unpredictably. The
Ashfall catastrophe sent volcanic clouds across the continent,
poisoned wells as far as the Great Northern Forest, and devastated
Kowloon's delta. Convoy marshals along Roc Road carry Hazard
Doctrine protocols copied from the Cinderteeth route houses --
the Silent Bell Protocol for resonance shifts, double-water
doctrine against contamination. These are not superstitions.
They are law written in the names of the dead.

Wall Command notes that the Chalkwind Saddles remain the only
viable commercial transit through the range. The Glasswash Fans
produce obsidian and sulfur that eastern markets prize. But every
trade route through the Cinderteeth passes near Conclave ruins,
and every ruin still hums with crystal residue that no living
authority maintains or monitors.

The Ash Cult claims eruptions are divine verdicts against civic
corruption -- a degraded echo of the Ventspeaker tradition,
stripped of its empirical discipline and loaded with apocalyptic
certainty. The Syndics classify them as a route hazard, not a
theological concern.

The Prism teaches: the Conclave did not fall because its research
was flawed. It fell because it operated beyond oversight. Kiess
exists because Evermeet trusted a sealed disc from an unaccountable
mountain authority, and paid for that trust in lives. We do not
repeat that transaction.
