The Cinderteeth -- As Kowloon Sees It

Temple Circle Memorial Registry, Ashfall Division

No region cuts deeper into Kowloon's memory than the Cinderteeth.
Those broken volcanic ridges are why this city exists. They are why
six hundred souls drowned in Yen-Mak. They are why we ink the
Neon Covenant in phosphorescent squid dye. Every institution we
have was forged in the aftermath of what those mountains did to us.

The Ashfall Monsoon was not a single event. Three years of black
volcanic rain choked our canals, collapsed roofs, turned fresh water
to sulfur. Kowloon's delta -- low, wet, open to the sky -- caught
the worst. The ash did not merely fall. It rained, mixing with
water to become poison in every channel of the Shallow Thousand.

The Temple Circle maintains the Ashfall Registry: six hundred names
from Yen-Mak, plus the uncounted dead from years one and two. Every
autumn during the Ashfall Vigil, those names are spoken aloud in
darkness. The Executioner strikes the covenant stone three times.
This is not ceremony. It is practice against forgetting.

The Jade Magistracy funds observers at the Chalkwind Saddles who
report tremor frequency and gas color. The Ventspeakers -- highland
people who read volcanic vents as practical geology -- have our
respect. When the Ash Cult claims eruptions are divine verdicts,
the Temple Circle replies: "Verdicts do not drown children."

The Spirebound Conclave embedded resonance crystals in the
Bellspine ridge and abandoned them. The Courier Lantern Office marks
this as institutional negligence -- instruments left running
without keepers, potentially amplifying the seismic coupling that
drove our Ashfall. We do not forgive this.

The Silent Bell Protocol and Double-water doctrine are mountain
law, but Kowloon adopted both for harbor emergency codes. When the
bay bells ring a certain pattern, every dock crew knows: stop,
separate, do not share water. We learned this from the dead.

Six subregions fill our hazard registry: the Ember Crown of
active calderas, the Bellspine where abandoned crystals ring, the
Chalkwind Saddles where our observers stand, the Glasswash Fans
of obsidian and sulfur, the Blackstep Footholds where mountain
meets civic law, and the Western Fold of smoldering Conclave ruins.

The mountains are not finished. The deep fault runs beneath the
continent. The Jade Magistracy's standing order is simple:
watch the mountains, always.
