The Cinderteeth: Where the Paradise Broke

From the Ember Warden Field Archive
Recorded at the Ash Memorial, Bloom Pavilion

Every child in Rakuen learns the Ash-and-Iron before they learn
the Paradise Thesis. This is deliberate. You must know what
killed the orchards before you can understand what the orchards meant.

The Cinderteeth Mountains are a volcanic arc running west to
northeast in broken tooth-ridges. They are beautiful at distance.
The Ember Wardens who chose their name did not choose it for the
beauty. They chose it because the mountains ate our future.

When the eruptions came, ash clouds crossed the continent. Midgaard
recorded the event in six ledger volumes of logistics failures.
Kowloon lost its delta settlement to the Ashfall Monsoon. The
Great Northern Forest lost a third of its game.

Rakuen lost everything.

The ash settled into our cisterns. Elys Savan's cooperative waterworks
-- the pride of the Southward Compact -- became poison delivery
systems. The orchards that had fed three generations choked on sulfur
rain. The Festival of Ever-Bloom was cancelled for the first time,
and the silence where the music should have been is still remembered
in the Ash Requiem sung each anniversary at the Bloom Pavilion.

The Spirebound Conclave had embedded resonance crystals at fault
intersections throughout the Bellspine ridge, claiming to monitor
seismic precursors. When the Conclave collapsed, those instruments
were abandoned. No one monitored. No one warned. The Ventspeakers
who had maintained interpretive relationships with the volcanic vents
-- who read gas color and tremor rhythm as practical geology -- had
already been displaced by institutions that valued measurement over
listening.

The Garden Ledger Clerks keep a sealed jar of ash from the worst
season beside the pressed flowers of the last full bloom. The contrast
is the lesson: this is what we grew, and this is what fell from
the sky to kill it.

During the Ash-and-Iron decades, Rakuen was forced to adopt ration
towers, labor drafts, and salvage courts. Every mechanism the Paradise
Thesis had rejected became necessary for survival. We became, for a
terrible season, exactly what we had been founded to refuse.

The Ash Cult in the mountains claims eruptions pronounce divine
verdict against civic corruption. The Ember Wardens have a quieter
reading: the mountains do not judge. They simply burn. The
judgment belongs to those who knew the ash would fall and chose
not to share the warning. The judgment belongs to those who watched
our cisterns darken and offered us three refusals instead of
one outstretched hand.

The Cracked Promise Stones nearest the mountain road bear the
deepest fractures. The Ember Wardens say the cracks point toward
the Cinderteeth. The Garden Ledger Clerks say they point toward
Midgaard. Both are correct. The ash came from one direction.
The abandonment came from the other.
