The Cinderteeth Mountains -- Quarantine Ledger Hazard Assessment

The Quarantine Ledger maintains a permanent advisory on the
Cinderteeth range. Classification: Systemic Supply Chain Threat,
Tier One. No other geographic feature has disrupted Mafdet's
commerce as consistently or as catastrophically.

The Ashfall is not ancient history to our Ledger Houses. It is
the event that wrote our emergency protocols. When ash poisoned
wells and streams, the inland trade network collapsed for years.
Caravans stopped. The oasis corridor dried up -- not of water, but
of goods. Our harbor sat open and empty. The Sand-Sea Carters'
Guild nearly dissolved during the second Ash Winter.

We rebuilt. But every Hazard Scribe knows the lesson: volcanic
risk is supply chain risk. A caldera that erupts in the western
mountains empties our eastern docks three seasons later.

The Spirebound Conclave's abandoned resonance crystals in the
Bellspine ridge are unattested artifacts of unknown function.
None have been cataloged, because the Conclave collapsed without
filing a single manifest. Under the Dual-Attestation Protocol, any
crystal fragment reaching our port from the Cinderteeth requires
Tier Three quarantine -- inland provenance unverifiable, maritime
risk classification high-unknown.

The Ventspeakers who once read volcanic behavior interest our
Harbor Wardens as a lost early-warning network. Their polished
name-stones at vent mouths function as attestation markers --
proof that someone maintained a watching relationship with specific
vents. That relationship is broken. No one reads the mountain's
moods with their rigor.

The Hazard Doctrine practiced at mountain route houses -- the
Silent Bell Protocol, the double-water doctrine -- is sound
logistics discipline. Our own harbor chain operates on similar
principles: when conditions change, halt, verify, and proceed only
under attestation. The mountain people learned this from disaster.
So did we.

The Ash Cult's claim that eruptions are divine verdicts is the
kind of unattested assertion the Shrine of the First Claw was built
to reject. The mountain does not judge. It erupts. The difference
matters.

